<a name="ss2"></a>
					        
<h4>Showing or Hiding the File Extension</h4>

					        <p>In Computer Basics, you learned about file names and file
					        extensions. To review, file names have two parts:</p>
					
					        <p>1. <strong>File name</strong> - whatever name the computer user chooses</p>
					
					        <p>2. <strong>File extension</strong> - tells the user the type of file it is, like .doc
					        or .xls</p>
					
					        <p>Remember, you do not add the extension to the file name. The program
					        you use to save the data will add the file extension for you.</p>
					
					        <p>Let's start by opening up your C: drive and looking at some files to
					        see if the file extension is showing or not.</p>
					
					        <p>With your C: drive open on the screen, you will need to double click
					        on one of the folders in the root directory. If there are no files,
					        only folders, you will need to double click on another folder until you
					        find a folder that has some files in it.</p>

<p> In the examples below the first one has <strong>no file extensions</strong> and the second one has <strong> file extensions showing.</strong></p>
	




				
					        <p><img class="space" src=
					        "images/filesandfolders/nofileextension.jpg">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
					        <img class="space" src=
					        "images/filesandfolders/fileextensionshown.jpg"></p>
					
					        <p>In the viewing options, you can choose to view file names in the C:
					        Drive or in any other storage location or device either with the file
					        extension or without it. These viewing options are found in the
					        <strong>Folder Options</strong>.The Folder Options Box is the same for
					        all versions of Windows, so you just have to locate it in your
					        version.</p>



<p>Let's look at the Folder Options box for all versions and then we will locate it in each of the versions.</p> 

			                <hr>
			            </div>
			        </div>

 


